The String Basis 

In this section we investigate some properties of
the  quantum mechanics.
Of paramount importance is
the relation

S H = H^S, S = e^g_2  ,
 
to be proven below.
Let us explain the significance of this result.  We
saw in section 2 that the Hamiltonian  is not hermitian
with respect to the inner product .  However, this is
no cause for concern: while  is manifestly hermitian
with respect to the gauge theory inner product 
 of , there is no reason for it to
be hermitian with respect to  since the
two inner products agree only at !

It is believed that the gauge theory inner product at finite 
(defined by )
is given by the simple formula

1  2 _g_2  = 1  S  2 .
 
The relation  guarantees that  is hermitian with
respect to .  This provides a consistency check
on the conjecture that  is actually the correct gauge theory
inner product at finite .

