Hamiltonian in the string basis 

The basis which diagonalizes the inner product  is 

 a  = S^-1/2  a .
 
This basis has been identified as the basis of string states
in the light-cone string field theory:
if 
corresponds to an operator with precisely
 traces, then 
corresponds to a state of precisely
 strings.

It is convenient to
define an operator  whose matrix elements in
the gauge theory basis are the same as the matrix elements of
the Hamiltonian  in the string basis:

a   H  b  _g_2 
= a  H    b.
 
We will call  the 'string Hamiltonian',
since its matrix elements are related to matrix elements
of the light-cone string field theory Hamiltonian.
Clearly,  is given by

H  = S^1/2  H S^-1/2 .
 
Setting  in
 leads to

H  = H_0 + g_2 2  ( V + V^) +
g_2^2 8  [ , V - V^].
 
Naturally,  is manifestly hermitian with respect
to the inner product .
It is remarkable that whereas the Hamiltonian
in the gauge theory basis has no contact terms,
the basis transformation introduces
a single  contact
term.

The 'supercharge' 

Remarkably, it is easy to see that the string Hamiltonian 
is a perfect square!  In particular,

H  = Q^Q, Q = Q_0 + g_2 2  [Q_0,]
= S^-1/2  Q_0 S^1/2 .
 
The order  term in  works out due to , while the
